<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="148" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1194,1689]" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1338,1364]" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Colony composed of several short and curved side branches with short internodes, densely arranged polyps that are conical to cylindrical, and a thick, tough, possibly collagenous layer covering the coenenchyme (
<bibRefCitation author="Duenas, L. F. &amp; Alderslade, P. &amp; Sanchez, J. A." box="[159,608,1411,1437]" pageId="11" pageNumber="148" pagination="15 - 28" refId="ref9041" refString="Duenas, L. F., Alderslade, P. &amp; Sanchez, J. A. (2014) Molecular systematics of the deep-sea bamboo corals (Octocorallia: Isididae: Keratoisidinae) from New Zealand with descriptions of two new species of Keratoisis. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 74, 15 - 28. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2014.01.031" type="journal article" year="2014">Dueñas, Alderslade, and Sanchez, 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="148" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1194,1689]" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1447,1473]" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">Remarks</emphasis>
. The specimens collected from Tasmania displayed the morphological characters previously described for the species (
<figureCitation box="[417,547,1483,1509]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1155,1179]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,309,1122]" captionTargetId="figure-94@12.[151,1435,309,1132]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 11. Onkoisis magnifica, specimen K3830, A, view of preserved polyps, B, piece of external tunic with embedded sclerites, C, light microscope image of tunic and calcareous nodules. Onkoisis solitaria, D, E, individual polyps, with surface and transmitted illumination showing scale sclerites on lower portion of polyp body." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877197/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">Fig.11A–C</figureCitation>
). The rods in the polyps in the Tasmanian material are larger on one side of the polyp body than the other, and nodes are thick on one side of the axis and thin on the other. The colony branches at the internodes with occasional proximal nodes on the branches. Polyps on the younger branches are densely packed and embedded in the coenenchyme, while polyps at the older base of the colony are spaced out, separated by a thin coenenchyme. The polyps and coenenchyme are covered with a collagenous tunic in which are embedded numerous small calcareous nodules (
<figureCitation box="[446,580,1663,1689]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1155,1179]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,309,1122]" captionTargetId="figure-94@12.[151,1435,309,1132]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 11. Onkoisis magnifica, specimen K3830, A, view of preserved polyps, B, piece of external tunic with embedded sclerites, C, light microscope image of tunic and calcareous nodules. Onkoisis solitaria, D, E, individual polyps, with surface and transmitted illumination showing scale sclerites on lower portion of polyp body." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877197/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">Fig. 11B, C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
